1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,835
Hello, friends!

2
00:00:00,835 --> 00:00:03,751
One of the world's most courageous military commanders

3
00:00:06,129 --> 00:00:08,700
widely recognized as the most powerful king in Europe.

4
00:00:14,968 --> 00:00:17,121
was Napoleon Bonaparte.

5
00:00:17,121 --> 00:00:20,113
However, he remains one of history's most controversial figures,

6
00:00:20,113 --> 00:00:23,466
with some praising his capabilities

7
00:00:23,466 --> 00:00:28,698
while others criticize his hunger for power.

8
00:00:28,698 --> 00:00:31,904
Questions about the immense loss of life attributed to him persist:

9
00:00:31,904 --> 00:00:33,298
What is the truth?

10
00:00:33,298 --> 00:00:37,181
Was he a hero of the masses or the vilest of villains?

11
00:00:37,181 --> 00:00:42,864
Director Ridley Scott is set to release 
a film titled 'Napoleon' on November 24th.

12
00:00:42,864 --> 00:00:47,991
Scott, known for directing acclaimed films 
such as 'Gladiator,' 'The Martian,' and 'Prometheus,'

13
00:00:47,991 --> 00:00:50,535
the trailer of the film promises an intriguing portrayal,

14
00:00:50,535 --> 00:00:54,229
featuring Joaquin Phoenix as Napoleon.

15
00:00:54,229 --> 00:00:57,644
Phoenix notably played the role of 
Joker in the film of the same name.

16
00:00:57,644 --> 00:00:59,838
So I thought this is the perfect time

17
00:00:59,838 --> 00:01:05,289
to get to know Napoleon Bonaparte's story.

18
00:01:14,331 --> 00:01:18,361
Napoleon was born on 15th August 1769,

19
00:01:18,361 --> 00:01:20,331
on the island of Corsica.

20
00:01:20,331 --> 00:01:24,805
Look at the map, it is an island 
situated between France and Italy.

21
00:01:24,805 --> 00:01:28,364
Noteworthy for being the backdrop of the song Matargasti,

22
00:01:28,364 --> 00:01:31,112
from the film Tamasha starring 
Ranbir Kapoor and Deepika Padukone.

23
00:01:31,688 --> 00:01:35,231
Corsica, during the 1700s,

24
00:01:35,231 --> 00:01:38,731
was under the rule of a country that doesn't exist any longer.

25
00:01:38,731 --> 00:01:40,731
Republic of Genoa.

26
00:01:40,820 --> 00:01:43,093
This was the flag of the Republic of Genoa.

27
00:01:43,093 --> 00:01:46,439
Several territories that are now part of Italy and Greece 

28
00:01:46,439 --> 00:01:48,011
were under the control of this country.

29
00:01:48,011 --> 00:01:50,269
One such territory was Corsica,

30
00:01:50,269 --> 00:01:53,058
but the Corsicians were fed up with Genoan rule.

31
00:01:53,058 --> 00:01:56,194
They were fueled by a burgeoning sense of nationalism

32
00:01:56,194 --> 00:01:58,529
and a desire to live in a free country.

33
00:01:58,529 --> 00:02:03,705
Pasquale Paoli emerged as a leader in 
the Corsican struggle for independence,

34
00:02:03,705 --> 00:02:06,652
and a young Napoleon embraced Corsican nationalism,

35
00:02:06,652 --> 00:02:08,972
inspired by his childhood idol Paoli.

36
00:02:08,972 --> 00:02:12,601
By the 1760s, Corsica found itself embroiled in war,

37
00:02:12,601 --> 00:02:14,908
while the Republic of Genoa,

38
00:02:14,908 --> 00:02:18,749
burdened by debt and war,

39
00:02:18,749 --> 00:02:27,336
decided to literally sell the island of Corsica to France in 1768.

40
00:02:27,336 --> 00:02:29,925
This decision caused unrest among Corsican freedom fighters,

41
00:02:29,925 --> 00:02:32,116
but there wasn't much that they could do.

42
00:02:32,116 --> 00:02:35,724
Resisting the might of France's imperial power proved challenging.

43
00:02:35,724 --> 00:02:40,086
The turning point came in 1769 when 
the French army clashed with Corsican forces.

44
00:02:40,086 --> 00:02:42,242
During the Battle of Ponte Novu.

45
00:02:42,242 --> 00:02:45,216
Following a swift victory, France 

46
00:02:45,216 --> 00:02:48,459
claimed Corsica as its territory.

47
00:02:48,459 --> 00:02:50,602
Shortly thereafter, Napoleon Bonaparte was born.

48
00:02:50,602 --> 00:02:52,271
His father Carlo,

49
00:02:52,271 --> 00:02:57,342
was a lawyer who initially fought 
alongside Corsican freedom fighters.

50
00:02:57,342 --> 00:03:00,286
But after the French army's triumph

51
00:03:00,286 --> 00:03:02,917
Paoli had to flee the country.

52
00:03:02,917 --> 00:03:06,614
And Carlo switched allegiance.

53
00:03:06,614 --> 00:03:10,043
The shift was notable, as Carlo became an 
ardent supporter of the French royalty.

54
00:03:10,043 --> 00:03:13,457
He used connections to make advances in his career.

55
00:03:13,457 --> 00:03:16,016
He secured the status of Nobility.

56
00:03:16,016 --> 00:03:20,415
By 1777, he became Corsica's representative 

57
00:03:20,415 --> 00:03:24,176
to the court of the new French king, Louis XVI.

58
00:03:24,176 --> 00:03:26,444
This transformation bothered Napoleon.

59
00:03:26,444 --> 00:03:28,691
He harboured no fondness for his father.

60
00:03:28,691 --> 00:03:32,635
He viewed his father as a coward and deserter. 

61
00:03:36,129 --> 00:03:39,001
But it was his father's connections that

62
00:03:39,001 --> 00:03:41,840
Napoleon and his brother Joseph secured scholarships,

63
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:46,617
enabling Napoleon to enrol in the French Military College.

64
00:03:46,617 --> 00:03:50,608
At the college, Napoleon was surrounded 
by the children of French aristocrats,

65
00:03:50,608 --> 00:03:53,373
he faced ridicule at school

66
00:03:53,373 --> 00:03:55,104
due to his distinctive accent.

67
00:03:55,104 --> 00:03:57,821
Unfazed, he refrained from socialising with his peers,

68
00:03:57,821 --> 00:04:01,521
viewing the French as colonizers.

69
00:04:01,521 --> 00:04:06,423
His dream was to witness his country, Corsica achieve independence. 

70
00:04:06,423 --> 00:04:11,372
Napoleon's isolation drove him to find solace in books,

71
00:04:11,372 --> 00:04:16,503
particularly drawn to Enlightenment-age
philosopher Jean-Jacques Rousseau,

72
00:04:16,503 --> 00:04:20,772
the primary reason for that was 
Rousseau wrote about Corsican freedom,

73
00:04:20,772 --> 00:04:22,954
and considered the Corsicians brave in his writings.

74
00:04:22,954 --> 00:04:24,410
In addition to philosophy,

75
00:04:24,410 --> 00:04:27,281
Napoleon exhibited a keen interest in mathematics, history, and geography,

76
00:04:27,281 --> 00:04:30,725
excelling in these subjects.

77
00:04:30,725 --> 00:04:34,399
Among his favourite reads was Plutarch's 'Parallel Lives,'

78
00:04:34,399 --> 00:04:38,161
a compilation of 45 biographies featuring historical figures

79
00:04:38,161 --> 00:04:42,191
like Alexander the Great and Julius Caesar.

80
00:04:42,191 --> 00:04:45,991
Napoleon found inspiration in Caesar, 
often drawing comparisons.

81
00:04:45,991 --> 00:04:47,391
Upon completing his schooling,

82
00:04:47,391 --> 00:04:49,602
Napoleon joined a military academy in Paris,

83
00:04:49,602 --> 00:04:51,414
specializing in artillery.

84
00:04:51,414 --> 00:04:57,334
Graduating as the second lieutenant 
of the Royal Artillery in the French army,

85
00:04:57,334 --> 00:05:01,150
during all of this, he would often return to Corsica

86
00:05:01,150 --> 00:05:04,480
continuing to idolize Pasquale Paoli.

87
00:05:04,480 --> 00:05:06,883
However, the landscape changed in 1789

88
00:05:06,883 --> 00:05:09,734
with the onset of the French Revolution.

89
00:05:11,499 --> 00:05:14,553
I have made a separate video on the French Revolution

90
00:05:14,553 --> 00:05:17,550
in case you haven't watched it,
you can watch it after this.

91
00:05:17,550 --> 00:05:22,326
During this period, Corsica fell under the 
jurisdiction of the new French National Assembly,

92
00:05:22,326 --> 00:05:24,742
leading to the pardon of Pasquale Paoli.

93
00:05:24,742 --> 00:05:27,598
After a 20-year exile, Paoli returned,

94
00:05:27,598 --> 00:05:30,605
and was greeted warmly by the people of Corsica

95
00:05:30,605 --> 00:05:32,433
including Napoleon.

96
00:05:32,433 --> 00:05:36,287
Subsequent elections in Corsica 
saw Pasquale Paoli emerge victorious,

97
00:05:36,287 --> 00:05:37,892
becoming the President.

98
00:05:37,892 --> 00:05:41,341
Despite Napoleon's 'traitorous' father having passed away by the time

99
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:44,346
and Napoleon holding Paoli in high regard,

100
00:05:44,346 --> 00:05:48,183
Paoli harboured resentment toward Napoleon's family,

101
00:05:48,183 --> 00:05:52,132
Consequently, Paoli declared that such 
traitorous families could not live in Corsica,

102
00:05:52,132 --> 00:05:54,547
prompting Napoleon and his family

103
00:05:54,547 --> 00:05:58,762
to relocate from Corsica to France

104
00:05:58,762 --> 00:06:00,767
in June 1793.

105
00:06:00,767 --> 00:06:05,062
Following this, Paoli severed ties with 
the French Revolutionary Assembly,

106
00:06:05,062 --> 00:06:07,859
aligning himself with their enemy, the British.

107
00:06:07,859 --> 00:06:10,303
This is why, in 1794,

108
00:06:10,303 --> 00:06:13,284
the Anglo-Corsican Kingdom was established,

109
00:06:13,284 --> 00:06:16,376
expelling France from Corsica

110
00:06:16,376 --> 00:06:19,906
and rendering it a puppet state under British control.

111
00:06:19,906 --> 00:06:21,869
However, this arrangement lasted only two years.

112
00:06:21,869 --> 00:06:24,797
In 1796, France launched an attack,

113
00:06:24,797 --> 00:06:28,476
reclaiming Corsica from British rule.

114
00:06:28,476 --> 00:06:31,214
Meanwhile, France was embroiled in a civil war,

115
00:06:31,214 --> 00:06:33,750
marked by various factions of

116
00:06:33,750 --> 00:06:36,790
French revolutionaries and counter-revolutionaries.

117
00:06:36,790 --> 00:06:39,095
People, divided into various groups,
were fighting among themselves.

118
00:06:39,095 --> 00:06:43,684
In 1793, a political group named Jacobins,

119
00:06:43,684 --> 00:06:46,258
came to power and formed the French government.

120
00:06:46,258 --> 00:06:50,304
The group was led by Maximillien Robespierre.

121
00:06:50,304 --> 00:06:51,378
During this tumultuous period,

122
00:06:51,378 --> 00:06:55,928
Napoleon expressed his support for the 
Jacobin government in a political pamphlet.

123
00:06:55,928 --> 00:06:59,394
This caught the attention of Robespierre's brother,

124
00:06:59,394 --> 00:07:01,806
it greatly impressed him. 

125
00:07:01,806 --> 00:07:05,033
This gave a boost to Napoleon's career prospects.

126
00:07:05,033 --> 00:07:07,899
In September 1793, an event occurred that

127
00:07:07,899 --> 00:07:10,092
further elevated Napoleon's popularity.

128
00:07:10,092 --> 00:07:12,346
Toulon, a French naval base,

129
00:07:12,346 --> 00:07:16,391
witnessed an uprising by a group

130
00:07:16,391 --> 00:07:19,771
and subsequent attacks by the British forces.

131
00:07:19,771 --> 00:07:23,694
The French Army dispatched Napoleon 
to take command at this location.

132
00:07:23,694 --> 00:07:27,364
Napoleon was then serving as 
Senior Gunner and Artillery Commander.

133
00:07:27,364 --> 00:07:30,151
Napoleon proposed a strategic plan to win 
this conflict 

134
00:07:30,151 --> 00:07:31,716
and shared it with his commanders.

135
00:07:31,716 --> 00:07:34,598
The plan included capturing a fort,

136
00:07:34,598 --> 00:07:39,287
securing a hill for artillery dominance,

137
00:07:39,287 --> 00:07:42,651
and launching attacks on British ships.

138
00:07:47,442 --> 00:07:49,341
His plan was executed

139
00:07:49,341 --> 00:07:51,604
with Napoleon fighting with remarkable bravery,

140
00:07:51,604 --> 00:07:53,497
and suffering significant injuries.

141
00:07:53,497 --> 00:07:56,276
but after three months of struggle,
the French army emerged victorious. 

142
00:07:56,276 --> 00:07:59,406
The General of the French Army, Dugomere, 
speaking about Napoleon, stated

143
00:07:59,406 --> 00:08:03,407
'I have no words to describe Bonaparte's merit:

144
00:08:03,407 --> 00:08:07,730
much technical skill, an equal degree 
of intelligence, and too much gallantry...

145
00:08:07,730 --> 00:08:09,095
Napoleon is an amazing man.'

146
00:08:09,095 --> 00:08:12,825
In recognition of his contributions, Napoleon 
was promoted to the rank of Brigadier General

147
00:08:12,825 --> 00:08:16,997
at the young age of 24.

148
00:08:16,997 --> 00:08:21,484
During this period, France remained 
embroiled in a civil war,

149
00:08:21,484 --> 00:08:25,032
and Maximilian Robespierre sought to implement reforms.

150
00:08:25,032 --> 00:08:27,064
Such as universal male suffrage,

151
00:08:27,064 --> 00:08:30,531
granting voting rights to all men above 18.

152
00:08:30,531 --> 00:08:32,605
While women were not granted political rights,

153
00:08:32,605 --> 00:08:35,097
significant reforms were instituted for them,

154
00:08:35,097 --> 00:08:37,268
including the right to divorce

155
00:08:37,268 --> 00:08:40,972
an option that was previously unavailable to women.

156
00:08:40,972 --> 00:08:44,794
Additionally, women gained access to 
the right to education and work opportunities.

157
00:08:44,794 --> 00:08:48,544
Robespierre's influence extended to the abolition of slavery in France

158
00:08:48,544 --> 00:08:51,852
and the French colonies,

159
00:08:51,852 --> 00:08:54,774
leaving a lasting impact reflected in

160
00:08:54,774 --> 00:09:00,541
numerous roads and metro stations 
named after him in France.

161
00:09:00,541 --> 00:09:04,419
However, Robespierre's tenure was marked by controversy,

162
00:09:04,419 --> 00:09:07,629
particularly because of the Reign of Terror.

163
00:09:07,629 --> 00:09:12,281
In an effort to quash opposition to the French Revolution,

164
00:09:12,281 --> 00:09:16,476
thousands were executed on suspicion alone,

165
00:09:16,476 --> 00:09:19,895
leading to the d3ath of at least 20,000 French citizens.

166
00:09:19,895 --> 00:09:24,481
Simultaneously, the government initiated the 
dismantling of Catholic Christianity in France.

167
00:09:24,481 --> 00:09:28,349
confiscating church properties

168
00:09:28,349 --> 00:09:32,392
and promoting a singular Supreme God,

169
00:09:32,392 --> 00:09:37,614
to be revered through acts of service to the people.

170
00:09:37,614 --> 00:09:39,828
Amid these challenges and instability,

171
00:09:39,828 --> 00:09:44,683
a coup unfolded in July 1794 against the Jacobins government,

172
00:09:44,683 --> 00:09:47,328
resulting in its complete overthrow

173
00:09:47,328 --> 00:09:50,120
and Robespierre's execution.

174
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:54,623
In August 1794, since Napoleon 
supported the toppled government,

175
00:09:54,623 --> 00:09:56,438
he was imprisoned.

176
00:09:56,438 --> 00:09:59,515
He vigorously defended himself,

177
00:09:59,515 --> 00:10:02,465
securing his release from jail after only a few weeks.

178
00:10:02,465 --> 00:10:05,418
The orchestrator of this coup was 
the well-known figure, Paul Barras,

179
00:10:05,418 --> 00:10:08,042
who had known Napoleon since the Siege of Toulon

180
00:10:08,042 --> 00:10:10,122
and gradually developed a favourable opinion of him.

181
00:10:10,122 --> 00:10:13,816
In October 1795, Napoleon was entrusted with the task of

182
00:10:13,816 --> 00:10:15,812
quelling a revolution,

183
00:10:15,812 --> 00:10:19,434
despite the French army facing 
a numerical disadvantage of 1 to 6.

184
00:10:19,434 --> 00:10:23,647
Employing 40 cannons and limited infantry,

185
00:10:23,647 --> 00:10:27,113
Napoleon successfully suppressed the uprising within 2 hours,

186
00:10:27,113 --> 00:10:31,369
This pleased Paul Barras,
who then gave him the title of General.

187
00:10:31,369 --> 00:10:33,700
Napoleon became a national hero.

188
00:10:37,194 --> 00:10:39,550
At just 27 years old,

189
00:10:39,550 --> 00:10:41,652
he assumed the role of General in the French Army.

190
00:10:41,652 --> 00:10:43,622
Shortly thereafter, he took command

191
00:10:43,622 --> 00:10:45,106
of the Army of Italy,

192
00:10:45,106 --> 00:10:46,672
not the Italian Army,

193
00:10:46,672 --> 00:10:50,640
Rather the French forces operating in Italy.

194
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:52,284
They were known as the Army of Italy.

195
00:10:52,284 --> 00:10:57,337
The troops lacked motivation, discipline, and supplies.

196
00:10:57,337 --> 00:11:01,284
Napoleon addressed this by delivering compelling speeches,

197
00:11:01,284 --> 00:11:04,037
emphasizing the importance of discipline for victory

198
00:11:04,037 --> 00:11:08,917
and condemning looting and pillaging in conquered territories,

199
00:11:08,917 --> 00:11:11,145
asserting that only cowards engage in such actions.

200
00:11:11,145 --> 00:11:14,313
Napoleon's armies didn't loot or pillage territories. 

201
00:11:14,313 --> 00:11:16,802
Despite this, Napoleon did indulge in 
one form of appropriation—art.

202
00:11:16,802 --> 00:11:18,023
That's right.

203
00:11:18,023 --> 00:11:22,885
His passion for art stemmed from his 
desire to establish a universal museum in Paris,

204
00:11:22,885 --> 00:11:26,290
showcasing a vast collection of 
artworks from around the world.

205
00:11:26,290 --> 00:11:30,198
In later years, he even renamed 
the Louvre Museum,

206
00:11:30,198 --> 00:11:32,503
naming the museum after himself.

207
00:11:32,503 --> 00:11:34,873
Getting back to the Army of Italy,

208
00:11:34,873 --> 00:11:38,322
Napoleon led them in a famous battle against the Austrians.,

209
00:11:38,322 --> 00:11:40,869
the Battle of Arcole.

210
00:11:40,869 --> 00:11:44,160
This famous painting depicts this battle.

211
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:46,608
Napoleon's tactics involved

212
00:11:46,608 --> 00:11:49,190
rapid troop movement, varied formations,

213
00:11:49,190 --> 00:11:52,039
and surprise attacks on the enemy.

214
00:11:52,039 --> 00:11:55,103
Using these, Napoleon's troops won the Battle of Arcole.

215
00:11:57,481 --> 00:12:03,096
In 1798, as France contemplated 
invading the British Isles,

216
00:12:03,096 --> 00:12:05,608
Napoleon, upon his return to Paris,

217
00:12:05,608 --> 00:12:07,637
refused to fight in this battle.

218
00:12:07,637 --> 00:12:11,084
He argued that the British Navy was formidable

219
00:12:11,084 --> 00:12:13,005
and it made any invasion impractical.

220
00:12:13,005 --> 00:12:15,161
He proposed an alternative campaign

221
00:12:15,161 --> 00:12:17,772
in the Mediterranean.

222
00:12:17,772 --> 00:12:20,814
Advancing southward to capture Egypt

223
00:12:20,814 --> 00:12:24,064
and blocking the route of the British to India.

224
00:12:24,064 --> 00:12:28,331
Afterwards, Napoleon planned to 
assist Tipu Sultan of Mysore

225
00:12:28,331 --> 00:12:29,875
in his struggle against the British.

226
00:12:29,875 --> 00:12:34,971
Commencing his Mediterranean campaign with 40,000 soldiers,

227
00:12:34,971 --> 00:12:40,116
Napoleon and his soldiers set sail for 
Toulon, boarding numerous ships.

228
00:12:40,116 --> 00:12:42,323
In addition to the soldiers,

229
00:12:42,323 --> 00:12:46,530
he brought along over 160 
scientists, scholars, and artists,

230
00:12:46,530 --> 00:12:53,895
aiming to document valuable knowledge acquired in new territories.

231
00:12:53,895 --> 00:12:56,860
The army progressed southward,

232
00:12:56,860 --> 00:12:59,786
capturing the island of Malta

233
00:12:59,786 --> 00:13:03,921
before landing on the Egyptian coast in Alexandria.

234
00:13:03,921 --> 00:13:07,149
Battles such as the Battle of Alexandria 
and the Battle of the Pyramids, unfolded.

235
00:13:07,149 --> 00:13:09,543
"Following the footsteps of Alexander, the Great,

236
00:13:09,543 --> 00:13:10,823
and Ceaser,

237
00:13:15,650 --> 00:13:17,151
and destined for greatness."

238
00:13:17,309 --> 00:13:21,411
Resulting in victories against the Ottoman army and local kings.

239
00:13:21,411 --> 00:13:25,022
The French flag flew over the Citadel of Qaitbay

240
00:13:25,022 --> 00:13:28,163
Look at these photos from present-day Egypt.

241
00:13:28,163 --> 00:13:30,680
Napoleon established the Institute of Egypt

242
00:13:30,680 --> 00:13:35,339
to systematically study the country's 
history, culture, and resources,

243
00:13:35,339 --> 00:13:40,477
concurrently promoting Enlightenment ideals in Egypt.

244
00:13:40,477 --> 00:13:43,125
However, the success of Napoleon's plan was short-lived.

245
00:13:43,125 --> 00:13:46,049
Within a few weeks, in August 1798,

246
00:13:46,049 --> 00:13:50,694
a formidable fleet of the British Navy attacked the French,

247
00:13:50,694 --> 00:13:52,806
leading to the destruction of numerous French ships

248
00:13:52,806 --> 00:13:54,260
and the d3ath of a French admiral

249
00:13:54,260 --> 00:13:57,772
in the Battle of the Nile,

250
00:13:57,772 --> 00:14:02,481
depicted in this historic painting
