00:18:02,919 --> 00:18:06,721
On a mule guided by a farmer.

322
00:18:06,721 --> 00:18:09,521
These propaganda paintings served a specific purpose:

323
00:18:09,521 --> 00:18:13,353
to show Napoleon as the hero crossing the Alps on a horse. 

324
00:18:13,353 --> 00:18:16,223
The aim of the propaganda was to

325
00:18:16,223 --> 00:18:18,616
advance Napoleon's ultimate goal

326
00:18:18,616 --> 00:18:21,251
his final ambition.

327
00:18:21,251 --> 00:18:22,497
To be on the throne.

328
00:18:27,829 --> 00:18:30,195
When Napoleon returned to France from Egypt,

329
00:18:30,195 --> 00:18:34,304
there was widespread conflict and corruption reports in France.

330
00:18:34,304 --> 00:18:37,803
Napoleon orchestrated a coup in November 1799.

331
00:18:37,803 --> 00:18:40,139
This led to the expulsion of the existing government

332
00:18:40,139 --> 00:18:42,748
and the establishment of a new Consulate government,

333
00:18:42,748 --> 00:18:45,577
with Napoleon as the First Consul of the new government.

334
00:18:45,577 --> 00:18:48,973
Two individuals were appointed as aiding consuls,

335
00:18:48,973 --> 00:18:51,504
and a new constitution was introduced in France.

336
00:18:51,504 --> 00:18:54,098
Most French citizens didn't disapprove of it

337
00:18:54,098 --> 00:18:56,406
due to the widespread influence of propaganda,

338
00:18:56,406 --> 00:19:01,609
portraying Napoleon as a figure transcending politics,

339
00:19:01,609 --> 00:19:04,453
acting solely in the French national interest,

340
00:19:04,453 --> 00:19:08,736
and championing Enlightenment ideas.

341
00:19:08,736 --> 00:19:12,130
To solidify public approval on the new Constitution, 

342
00:19:12,130 --> 00:19:14,529
a referendum was held in France,

343
00:19:14,529 --> 00:19:20,035
and the results, announced by Napoleon's brother 
Lucien, the Minister of Interiors in France

344
00:19:20,035 --> 00:19:27,054
that 99.9% of the 3,013,000 voters

345
00:19:27,054 --> 00:19:29,346
supported the new constitution.

346
00:19:29,346 --> 00:19:34,386
It shows that 99.9% of the French citizens favoured Napoleon. 

347
00:19:34,386 --> 00:19:36,276
Was that true?
Absolutely not.

348
00:19:36,276 --> 00:19:40,216
In reality, approximately 1.5 million votes 
were cast in favour of Napoleon.

349
00:19:40,216 --> 00:19:45,552
French historian Claude Langlois presented evidence in 1972,

350
00:19:45,552 --> 00:19:49,736
revealing that the 1800 referendum was a complete fraud,

351
00:19:49,736 --> 00:19:54,059
with slightly over 50% of the votes cast
were in favour of Napoleon.

352
00:19:54,059 --> 00:19:58,339
Two years later, another referendum took place in 1802,

353
00:19:58,339 --> 00:20:00,755
where Napoleon posed the question to the public:

354
00:20:00,755 --> 00:20:04,297
Should he be appointed Consul for Life?

355
00:20:04,297 --> 00:20:07,204
Once again, the public voted

356
00:20:07,204 --> 00:20:10,926
with "99.7% voters"

357
00:20:10,926 --> 00:20:14,071
supporting Napoleon to hold power for life.

358
00:20:14,071 --> 00:20:17,154
Even after two fraud referendums,
Napoleon sought further validation. 

359
00:20:17,154 --> 00:20:20,615
In 1804, a third referendum was conducted,

360
00:20:20,615 --> 00:20:25,922
asking if Napoleon should become the King of France.

361
00:20:25,922 --> 00:20:27,933
And the result of the referendum was that,

362
00:20:27,933 --> 00:20:31,239
"99.9% of the voters"

363
00:20:31,239 --> 00:20:34,839
voted in favour of Napoleon becoming the king.

364
00:20:34,839 --> 00:20:39,262
Napoleon wasn't greedy for the power,

365
00:20:39,262 --> 00:20:42,261
but became the King to appease the masses.

366
00:20:42,261 --> 00:20:45,141
I'm kidding, that's not how it went.

367
00:20:45,141 --> 00:20:50,128
Napoleon wasn't one to hide his greed for power.

368
00:20:50,128 --> 00:20:53,185
He openly embraced his love for power,

369
00:20:53,185 --> 00:20:56,186
famously declaring, 'Power is my mistress.

370
00:20:56,186 --> 00:20:58,795
I have worked too hard at her conquest

371
00:20:58,795 --> 00:21:01,897
to allow anyone to take her away from me.'

372
00:21:07,265 --> 00:21:10,369
Back then, this hunger for power,

373
00:21:10,369 --> 00:21:14,729
was a characteristic accepted among 
kings and nobles of the time.

374
00:21:14,729 --> 00:21:18,122
Over the next decade, driven by Napoleon's love for power

375
00:21:18,122 --> 00:21:21,791
he engaged in a series of battles across Europe,

376
00:21:21,791 --> 00:21:24,269
interspersed with peace treaties,

377
00:21:24,269 --> 00:21:27,775
such as the one signed with Britain in 1802.

378
00:21:27,775 --> 00:21:30,127
However, the resumption of wars was inevitable

379
00:21:30,127 --> 00:21:32,172
as both Napoleon and the British thirsted for power.

380
00:21:32,172 --> 00:21:35,772
Many European nations engaged in wars with Napoleon 

381
00:21:35,772 --> 00:21:39,910
not only for power but also for their survival.

382
00:21:39,910 --> 00:21:44,465
Many European kings and monarchs felt 
threatened by the French revolutionary ideology.

383
00:21:44,465 --> 00:21:47,974
They considered Napolean a threat to their kingdom.

384
00:21:47,974 --> 00:21:50,304
In the French Revolution video, I explained that

385
00:21:50,304 --> 00:21:55,293
the ideology of Nationalism was introduced by the Enlightenment thinkers.

386
00:21:55,293 --> 00:21:57,157
Such as Rousseau and Voltaire.

387
00:21:57,157 --> 00:21:59,952
These were the ideologies of left-wing revolutionaries.

388
00:21:59,952 --> 00:22:06,594
While the right-wing adhered to 
supporting monarchies and social hierarchy,

389
00:22:06,594 --> 00:22:09,929
preserving the existing system.

390
00:22:09,929 --> 00:22:13,592
The left-wing ideology championed equality,

391
00:22:13,592 --> 00:22:17,144
freedom, and the aspiration for national freedom,

392
00:22:17,144 --> 00:22:20,865
evolving into the foundation of Republicanism.

393
00:22:20,865 --> 00:22:22,521
This nationalist fervour

394
00:22:22,521 --> 00:22:25,350
was quickly spreading across other 
European nations during that period,

395
00:22:25,350 --> 00:22:27,683
leading to the emergence of revolutionaries

396
00:22:27,683 --> 00:22:30,276
challenging the reigning monarchies.

397
00:22:30,852 --> 00:22:34,178
In response, these monarchs formed coalitions,

398
00:22:34,178 --> 00:22:38,642
sparking a series of coalition wars 
between 1792 and 1815,

399
00:22:38,642 --> 00:22:40,857
where monarchies collectively waged war against France.

400
00:22:40,857 --> 00:22:44,080
In this context, Napoleon's role can be seen as

401
00:22:44,080 --> 00:22:45,480
that of a liberator,

402
00:22:45,480 --> 00:22:49,724
propagating the slogans of freedom 
